project_specs.xml:7:    Ship a hardened, read-only relay agent — packaged as a multi-arch Docker image (causeflowai/relay) and versioned via semantic-release — that connects outbound from a customer's private network to the CauseFlow control plane over a single WebSocket /v1/relay/connect endpoint, executes JSON-RPC 2.0 requests (execute, list_resources, describe_resource, health_check) against configured PostgreSQL and MongoDB resources, enforces per-resource policy (allowlist + row limits) and SQL/aggregation safety, masks PII before results leave the network, emits a structured JSON audit trail, and reports resource updates + a 30s heartbeat. The image runs as non-root UID 10001 with a read-only filesystem, all Linux capabilities dropped, and no inbound ports.
project_specs.xml:11:    CauseFlow Relay is a small Node.js 22 / TypeScript agent deployed inside the customer's VPC or on-prem environment. It opens an outbound WebSocket connection to the CauseFlow control plane at /v1/relay/connect, authenticates with a per-tenant token, and surfaces a JSON-RPC 2.0 interface that the CauseFlow AI investigation agents use to read from the customer's own databases. The relay never accepts inbound connections, never publishes a public IP, and never writes to the customer databases — it enforces read-only at three layers (the driver interface contract, the SQL/AST parser that blocks DDL/DML/dangerous functions, and a `BEGIN READ ONLY` PostgreSQL transaction with a 30-second statement timeout; for MongoDB, `$out` and `$merge` aggregation stages are blocked). Per-resource policy decides which databases are reachable, which operations each one permits (query, describe_table, list_tables, explain), and the maximum rows per query. PII masking (CPF, email, credit card, bearer token, BR phone, plus user-defined regexes) runs on every result row before anything leaves the customer's network, so the control plane and AI agents only ever see sanitized data. Every request is logged as a structured JSON audit entry. The image is published to Docker Hub as `causeflowai/relay` for `linux/amd64` and `linux/arm64`, with version tags derived from Conventional Commits via semantic-release.
project_specs.xml:28:      - yaml — parses the `relay-config.yaml` file in `src/config/loader.ts`
project_specs.xml:35:      <database>None owned. The relay never persists; it reads from PostgreSQL and MongoDB instances the customer already runs, behind a per-resource `IReadOnlyDriver` port. Both PostgreSQL (via `pg`) and MongoDB (via `mongodb`) are customer-side resources; the relay never stores its own data.</database>
project_specs.xml:43:      Outbound WebSocket to the CauseFlow control plane at `${controlPlane.url}` (default `ws://localhost:3000/v1/relay/connect` for local dev, `wss://<host>/v1/relay/connect` in production). Connection URL carries `?token=<RELAY_TOKEN>&tenantId=<TENANT_ID>`; headers carry `Authorization: Bearer <token>` and `X-Tenant-Id: <tenantId>`. JSON-RPC 2.0 in both directions: control-plane → relay methods are `execute`, `list_resources`, `describe_resource`, `health_check`; relay → control-plane messages are `heartbeat` (every 30s) and `resource_update` (on connect and on change). All inbound messages are validated as JSON-RPC 2.0 before being handed to the dispatch switch in `src/index.ts`. Reconnect uses exponential backoff (1s → 30s max) on any non-intentional close.
project_specs.xml:52:      <security>Three-layer read-only enforcement: (1) `IReadOnlyDriver` interface contracts `validate` + `execute` and the relay never calls anything else; (2) `validateQuery` in `src/drivers/postgres/pg-query-parser.ts` parses the SQL with `node-sql-parser`, rejects anything that is not a single SELECT (or CTE/EXPLAIN), rejects semicolons that would split multi-statements, and rejects dangerous function names (`pg_sleep`, `pg_read_file`, `pg_write_file`, `pg_ls_dir`, `pg_stat_file`, `pg_terminate_backend`, `pg_cancel_backend`, `pg_reload_conf`, `dblink`, `dblink_exec`, etc.); (3) every `query` execution runs inside a `BEGIN READ ONLY` transaction with `SET statement_timeout = '30s'` and a server-enforced `LIMIT`. Connection pool: `max: 5`, `idleTimeoutMillis: 30000`, `connectionTimeoutMillis: 10000`. Customer supplies a read-only DB role; the relay never escalates.</security>
project_specs.xml:67:      <responsibility>Outbound-only WebSocket connection that delivers JSON-RPC 2.0 requests to the relay and receives `heartbeat` + `resource_update` messages back. The control plane is owned by the CauseFlow Core API and tracked there as RelayRegistry + WssRelayGateway. The relay never accepts inbound connections and never publishes a public IP.</responsibility>
project_specs.xml:90:      <deployment>CI runs on `ubuntu-latest` GitHub-hosted runners. Both workflows are versioned to commit-hash actions where possible (e.g. `actions/checkout@v4`); Docker login uses `docker/login-action@v3`, buildx uses `docker/build-push-action@v6`.</deployment>
project_specs.xml:113:      - Entry point (`src/index.ts`) wires drivers + engines + WS client, dispatches inbound JSON-RPC methods to the right engine, and installs `SIGINT` / `SIGTERM` graceful shutdown that closes the WS client, drains every driver's connection pool, and exits 0
project_specs.xml:126:      - PostgreSQL query parser (`src/drivers/postgres/pg-query-parser.ts`) uses `node-sql-parser` to AST-parse each query, reject any non-SELECT statement, reject multi-statement injection (semicolons splitting statements), and reject a hardcoded list of dangerous function names (`pg_sleep`, `lo_import`/`lo_export`, `pg_read_file`/`pg_write_file`/`pg_read_binary_file`, `pg_ls_dir`/`pg_stat_file`, `pg_terminate_backend`/`pg_cancel_backend`/`pg_reload_conf`, `set_config`/`current_setting`, `dblink`/`dblink_exec`); falls back to a textual first-word check (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE/DROP/ALTER/CREATE/TRUNCATE/GRANT/REVOKE/COPY → reject) if the parser cannot parse the statement
project_specs.xml:132:      - `PolicyEngine` (`src/policy/policy-engine.ts`) built from the resource list at startup; `evaluate(resourceId, command)` runs three checks in order: (1) resource exists in the config, (2) operation is in the resource's `allowedOperations`, (3) for `query`, the requested `limit` does not exceed `maxRowsPerQuery` (the driver then clamps it to `min(requested, max)`)
project_specs.xml:151:      - `resource_update` on connect (and on any future resource change): `{ type: 'resource_update', relayId, tenantId, resources: [{ resourceId, type, name, database, readOnly: true }] }` — tells the control plane which databases this relay can reach
project_specs.xml:152:      - Both messages are constructed via `createHeartbeat` and `createResourceUpdate` in `src/transport/protocol.ts` and sent via `WsClient.send`; the relay never sends JSON-RPC responses for its own messages
project_specs.xml:155:      - On `SIGINT` or `SIGTERM`, the entry point sets `intentionalClose` on the WS client (so the close does not trigger reconnect), closes the WebSocket, awaits `close()` on every driver, and exits 0
project_specs.xml:169:      <description>`npx tsc --noEmit` exits 0; the project compiles under `strict: true` with `module: NodeNext` and `moduleResolution: NodeNext`. `package.json` declares `"type": "module"` and every internal import uses the explicit `.js` extension on the relative path (e.g. `from './transport/protocol.js'`).</description>
project_specs.xml:175:      <description>When no YAML file is present at `RELAY_CONFIG_PATH` and `/app/relay-config.yaml`, `loadConfig()` falls back to building the config from environment variables: it reads `CONTROL_PLANE_URL` (default `ws://localhost:3000/v1/relay/connect`), `RELAY_TOKEN`, `TENANT_ID`, walks `RESOURCE_0_*` / `RESOURCE_1_*` / ... until a `RESOURCE_N_ID` is missing, JSON-parses each `RESOURCE_N_CONNECTION`, and uses `RESOURCE_N_MAX_ROWS` (default 1000). The fallback config round-trips through the same Zod schema as the YAML path.</description>
project_specs.xml:187:      <description>`release.config.js` chains the documented semantic-release plugins in order: `@semantic-release/commit-analyzer` → `@semantic-release/release-notes-generator` → `@semantic-release/changelog` (writes CHANGELOG.md) → `@semantic-release/npm` (with `npmPublish: false`, only updates `package.json` version) → `@semantic-release/git` (commits `package.json` + `CHANGELOG.md` back with the `chore(release): ${nextRelease.version} [skip ci]` message) → `@semantic-release/github` (creates the GitHub Release). `branches: ['main']` restricts releases to the main branch.</description>
project_specs.xml:208:      <description>On a `message` event, the `WsClient` JSON-parses the payload (string or buffer). Messages that fail to parse are logged at warn with the parse error and dropped. Messages where `parsed.jsonrpc !== '2.0'` or `parsed.method` is missing are likewise dropped. Only well-formed JSON-RPC 2.0 requests are forwarded to `opts.onMessage`.</description>
project_specs.xml:211:      <description>A JSON-RPC 2.0 `list_resources` request (no params) returns a list of resources shaped as `{ resourceId, type, name, database, readOnly: true }[]` derived from the policy engine's resource list. The response uses `createResponse(request.id, resources)`, producing `{ jsonrpc: '2.0', id, result: [...] }`.</description>
project_specs.xml:286:      <description>User-defined patterns from `masking.patterns` are added to the default set. A config with `{ name: 'session_id', regex: 'sess_[a-f0-9]{16}', replacement: 'sess_***' }` causes the string `sess_0123456789abcdef` to be masked to `sess_***` and the response `maskedFieldCount` to include this match.</description>
project_specs.xml:301:      <description>Sending `SIGTERM` (or `SIGINT`) to a running relay triggers the shutdown handler: `WsClient.close()` is invoked first (which sets `intentionalClose = true`, clears the heartbeat interval and reconnect timer, and closes the WebSocket), then `driver.close()` is awaited for every initialized driver (errors are caught and ignored), then `process.exit(0)`. A second `SIGTERM` after the first completes has no effect (the process is already gone).</description>
project_specs.xml:343:    1. On start, `loadConfig()` reads `RELAY_CONFIG_PATH` (or `/app/relay-config.yaml`) and parses it through Zod. If the file is missing, it builds a config from `RELAY_TOKEN` / `TENANT_ID` / `CONTROL_PLANE_URL` and the `RESOURCE_N_*` env-var family.
project_specs.xml:351:    5. On `SIGINT` / `SIGTERM`, the relay closes the WS client (without triggering a reconnect), closes every driver, and exits 0.
