+  <open-source-local-runtime>
+    - Goal: the relay subproject runs end-to-end via `docker compose up` from this repo root with zero paid/external SaaS credentials configured. The relay is already free of AWS, Stripe, Clerk, Sentry, Langfuse, Svix, Slack, Composio, and Mastra — the work here is to make that verifiable at a real docker-compose boundary and to add a local control-plane stub + local customer databases so the full JSON-RPC path can be exercised without any external service.
+    - Local control plane stub: a small `node:22-alpine` + `ws` service committed at `scripts/control-plane-stub/server.mjs` and wired into `docker-compose.yml` as the `relay-control-plane-stub` service. It listens on `0.0.0.0:3000` and answers the same `/v1/relay/connect` JSON-RPC 2.0 contract the CauseFlow control plane does: it accepts the relay's WebSocket handshake, validates the `?token=&tenantId=` query string against a fixed expected pair, logs every `resource_update` and `heartbeat` it receives, and on connect runs a `health_check` round-trip plus an `execute` against the bundled `order-pg` resource. No AWS, Stripe, Clerk, or any other vendor SDK is imported; only `ws` and the Node stdlib.
+    - Local customer databases: a `postgres:16-alpine` container (`relay-postgres`, port 5432) seeded by `scripts/control-plane-stub/initdb/01-orders.sql` with a small `orders` table for the demo `execute` path, and a `mongo:7` container (`relay-mongo`, port 27017) with no seed (the `describe_table` round-trip works against an empty database). Both are customer-side resources — the relay never owns or persists data.
+    - `relay-config.docker.yaml` is committed and mounted into the relay container; it points `controlPlane.url` at `ws://relay-control-plane-stub:3000/v1/relay/connect` and the two `resources[]` at the local Postgres and Mongo via `host: relay-postgres` / `uri: mongodb://relay-mongo:27017`.
+    - `.env.example` is added at the repo root and contains only the relay's own env vars: `RELAY_TOKEN`, `TENANT_ID`, `CONTROL_PLANE_URL`, `PG_HOST`, `PG_PORT`, `PG_DATABASE`, `PG_USER`, `PG_PASSWORD`, `MONGO_URI`, `MONGO_DATABASE`, and the optional `MASKING_ENABLED` / `AUDIT_ENABLED` toggles. No `AWS_*`, `STRIPE_*`, `CLERK_*`, `LANGFUSE_*`, `SENTRY_*`, `SVIX_*`, `SLACK_*`, `COMPOSIO_*`, `MASTRA_*`, `SQS_*`, `DYNAMODB_*`, `STS_*`, or `KMS_*` entries.
+    - `docker compose up -d` from the relay repo root brings up exactly four services — `relay-control-plane-stub`, `relay-postgres`, `relay-mongo`, `relay` — and within 60 seconds the relay's boot log contains "Connected to control plane" and the stub's log contains one `[stub] resource_update from relayId=<uuid> resources=<n>` line. No outbound traffic to AWS, Stripe, Clerk, Sentry, Langfuse, Svix, Slack, Composio, or Mastra is attempted (verifiable by grepping the relay boot log for vendor hostnames; the only outbound URL the relay ever resolves is the local stub).
+    - The 50 original acceptance checks (AC-001 through AC-050) still pass: the hardened container still runs as UID 10001, the policy engine / masking engine / audit logger / Postgres / Mongo drivers are unchanged, the WebSocket transport still speaks JSON-RPC 2.0 with the documented `execute` / `list_resources` / `describe_resource` / `health_check` methods, and graceful shutdown still works. This context adds the open-source docker-compose plumbing on top of the existing single-image distribution; it does not rewrite the relay.
+  </open-source-local-runtime>
